20:36.560 --> 20:37.380
Okay, I'm with you.

20:37.380 --> 20:39.640
But the field has strict constraints.

20:40.180 --> 20:41.240
It is irreversible.

20:41.740 --> 20:47.740
You cannot simply run the math backward to magically restore the original pristine mud.

20:48.500 --> 20:49.760
So what do you encode?

20:50.160 --> 20:53.680
What does the Yarncrawler system actually save to the hard drive?

20:53.800 --> 20:54.060
Right.

20:54.180 --> 20:55.540
What's the actual data?

20:55.780 --> 21:00.980
It saves the minimal set of mathematical constraints needed to reconstruct that path.

21:01.100 --> 21:03.240
You don't save the final state itself.

21:03.500 --> 21:06.420
You save the instructions for how to recreate the state.

21:06.420 --> 21:07.100
Wait, wait.

21:07.180 --> 21:08.560
I need to make sure I'm following this.

21:08.920 --> 21:12.340
You're saying memory isn't a storage locker full of items.

21:12.920 --> 21:17.240
It's a set of instructions for how to rebuild an experience from scratch.

21:17.360 --> 21:17.820
Exactly.

21:18.080 --> 21:25.680
You are storing the recipe for the constraint closure over a generative field rather than storing the baked cake itself.

21:25.680 --> 21:26.160
Wow.

21:26.420 --> 21:28.040
Okay, that covers the first idea.

21:28.660 --> 21:30.000
Temporal provenance.

21:30.000 --> 21:34.200
The second idea MEME8 desperately wanted was interference.

21:34.680 --> 21:35.520
We talked about this.

21:35.860 --> 21:39.460
Memories reinforcing or contradicting each other like waves.

21:39.460 --> 21:49.220
The critique paper translates this into the RSVP framework as constraint composition via something called xylomorphic computation.

21:49.220 --> 21:56.100
This is where we finally replace MEME8's messy fake wave equations with rigorous mathematical logic.

21:56.840 --> 22:01.900
Memories interact through what the paper calls variational adjunction structure.

22:02.060 --> 22:03.040
That sounds daunting.

22:03.040 --> 22:08.380
I know it does, but it fundamentally boils down to a concept called entropy closure.

22:08.600 --> 22:10.060
Yes, entropy closure.

22:10.220 --> 22:12.080
Okay, I've been thinking about this.

22:12.640 --> 22:15.560
Let me try an analogy here to see if I have this right.

22:16.320 --> 22:18.100
Let's step away from math.

22:19.400 --> 22:21.360
Imagine you are throwing a dinner party.

22:21.440 --> 22:22.680
Okay, I love a dinner party.

22:22.680 --> 22:25.800
You invite two completely different friend groups.

22:26.600 --> 22:31.680
The first memory, the first friend group, has a very strict set of constraints.

22:32.520 --> 22:39.940
They are strict vegans, they only like quiet acoustic music, and they want to eat exactly at 6pm.

22:40.400 --> 22:41.100
Very specific.

22:41.540 --> 22:41.900
Very.

22:42.200 --> 22:45.900
Now, the second memory, the second group, also has constraints.

22:45.900 --> 22:54.780
They only eat smoked barbecue, they demand incredibly loud, heavy metal music, and they refuse to eat until midnight.

22:55.140 --> 22:58.260
A recipe for an absolute disaster of a party.

22:58.360 --> 22:58.880
Exactly.

22:59.080 --> 23:03.940
If you try to combine these two groups into one single party in one room, you fail.

23:04.200 --> 23:10.820
There is no single environment, no minimal entropy state, that satisfies both sets of constraints simultaneously.

23:11.460 --> 23:13.780
They are fundamentally incompatible.

23:14.020 --> 23:15.060
That is spot on.

23:15.060 --> 23:19.940
In the RSVP framework, that incompatibility is destructive interference.

23:20.520 --> 23:24.080
It's not a magical wave and avoid canceling another ways out.

23:24.440 --> 23:26.880
It's the mathematical failure of entropy closure.

23:27.600 --> 23:32.580
The two memories cannot be seamlessly composed without breaking the rules of the entire system.

23:32.720 --> 23:34.700
That is the perfect, perfect analogy.

23:35.280 --> 23:36.320
Now, let's look at the reverse.

23:36.800 --> 23:42.620
Constructive interference is when the two friend groups have overlapping, highly compatible constraints.

23:42.620 --> 23:46.800
Let's say group two also likes acoustic music and eating early.

23:47.520 --> 23:52.680
Combining them is easy, and it actually reduces the overall complexity of planning the party.

23:54.420 --> 24:03.180
Interference in this rigorous system is simply the mathematical success or failure of finding a shared minimal entropy state.

24:03.180 --> 24:05.440
So, no waves needed.

24:05.900 --> 24:08.780
It requires absolutely no wave metaphors at all.

24:09.140 --> 24:12.360
It is pure, computable, constraint logic.

24:12.700 --> 24:14.280
Which brings us to the third idea.

24:14.860 --> 24:15.500
Compression.

24:16.200 --> 24:22.940
Bem-8 claimed they could achieve 100 to 1 compression ratios, basically just throwing huge numbers at the wall.

24:22.940 --> 24:23.500
Right.

24:23.900 --> 24:29.400
The Flyxion paper argues that true compression isn't just approximation, it is projection.

24:29.840 --> 24:30.080
Yes.

24:30.600 --> 24:39.240
In the RSVP framework, compression is defined as a projection onto a subspace of constraint space that is sufficient to support specific queries.

24:39.900 --> 24:46.980
What that means in plain English is that compression is a function of use, not a static property of the content itself.

24:46.980 --> 24:52.960
So, it's like, let's say I have a highly detailed, vivid memory of a massive fantasy novel I just read.

24:53.080 --> 24:56.160
If you walk up to me and just ask, hey, did you like the book?

24:56.500 --> 25:00.700
I can answer that question using a massively compressed version of my memory.

25:01.120 --> 25:04.920
It's a projection that only cares about my overall emotional sentiment.

25:05.460 --> 25:07.240
A simple thumbs up or thumbs down.

25:07.420 --> 25:07.840
Exactly.

25:07.840 --> 25:21.900
But if you ask me, what was the protagonist's mother's maiden name in chapter 4, I need a much less compressed, much higher dimensional projection of that memory to scan for that specific detail.

25:22.320 --> 25:22.880
Precisely.

25:23.640 --> 25:34.040
The system dynamically reduces the constraint set to only what is absolutely necessary for the intended computational purpose in that exact millisecond.

25:34.160 --> 25:34.380
Yeah.

25:34.380 --> 25:38.040
The compression ratio isn't a fixed number like 100 to 1.

25:38.160 --> 25:38.280
Right.

25:38.580 --> 25:45.160
It is literally just the input dimensionality divided by the effective rank of the plenum dynamics at that moment.

25:45.260 --> 25:45.500
Right.

25:45.740 --> 25:52.640
When we design this artificial system, we choose a Lagrangian, which is a mathematical function summarizing the system's dynamics,

25:53.060 --> 25:58.960
whose spectral decay naturally yields the exact compression we need for the task at hand.

25:58.960 --> 26:04.980
And to tie all this temporal stuff together, the paper outlines a temporal encoding operator, which they label T.

26:05.340 --> 26:10.420
It maps text tokens into time signals using a specific reading rate, R of T.

26:10.760 --> 26:11.120
Yes.

26:11.300 --> 26:20.560
It actually mathematically factors in how fast the AI system reads the input, including micropauses for punctuation and sentence boundaries.

26:20.560 --> 26:28.560
And that temporal signal feeds directly into the plenum excitation operator, which is framed as a variational problem.

26:29.200 --> 26:31.560
It has to balance two competing goals.

26:32.380 --> 26:39.180
It minimizes fidelity to the raw input while also minimizing dynamical consistency with the field.

26:39.400 --> 26:40.260
So there's a trade-off.

26:40.260 --> 26:42.640
It's a constrained optimization problem.

26:42.840 --> 26:49.320
That is the actual, highly complex math required to make wave storage work on a microchip.

26:49.620 --> 26:53.220
Okay, so this RSVP constraint system is incredibly logical.

26:53.480 --> 26:54.080
It's rigid.

26:54.440 --> 26:55.160
It's mathematical.

